the Berlin is very popular in every strong tournament.} 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 (5.
d4 {As usual White also tried} Nd6 {One game featured} 6. Bxc6 (6. dxe5 Nxb5 7.
a4 Nbd4 8. Nxd4 d5 ({I always thought Black's easiest way to simple equality is
} 8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4 d5 {and indeed it proved to be very reliable for Black.})
9. Nxc6 {This leads to a fighting position.} bxc6 10. Nd2 (10. Qd3 {is another
popular line here.}) 10... Rb8 $5 $146 {this looks to me like a good novelty,
especially taking into account that Kryvoruchko failed to equalise in his
previous game after} (10... Be7 11. Nb3 O-O 12. Be3 Bf5 13. Qd2 $14 {1/2-1/2 
(43) Gharamian,T (2626)-Kryvoruchko,Y (2692) Heraklio 2017}) 11. b3 ({Now} 11.
Nb3 {is well met by} c5 $1) 11... Bf5 (11... Be7 $5 {looks good for Black.})
12. Re1 Bb4 13. Ba3 Bxa3 14. Rxa3 O-O 15. Nf1 c5 16. Ng3 Be6 {Black had no
problems in Naiditsch,A (2721)-Kryvoruchko,Y (2695) Batumi GEO 2018}) 6... dxc6
7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {, with the typical Berlin endgame.} 9. h3 Be7 10.
Nc3 Nh4 {A very popular line on top level.} 11. Nxh4 Bxh4 12. Be3 h5 13. Rad1+
Ke8 14. Ne2 Be7 {This is considered to be a reliable move.} ({Mickey had a
tough loss with} 14... b6 15. a4 c5 16. Nc3 {Vachier Lagrave,M (2796)-Adams,M 
(2751) Caleta 2017}) 15. f4 $146 {A new and aggressive approach} g6 16. Nd4 Bd7
({I don't see any problem with the natural} 16... Bc5) 17. f5 Bxf5 18. Nxf5
gxf5 19. Rxf5 h4 20. Kf2 $14 {White obtained a slight pull in Karjakin,S (2760)
-Adams,M (2712) Batumi GEO 2018, although Black was able to defend this
endgame successfully.}) 5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1 {but was able to prevail
in only one game.} Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 Bf6 10. Re1 Re8 {Here we have an
important crossroad. White tried three different moves.} 11. c3 (11. Rxe8+ Nxe8
12. d5 d6 13. Nd2 c6 $5 {Previously Black usually played either 13...Bf5 or 13.
..Bg5} 14. Nc4 $146 {A new attempt.} ({Before White only played} 14. Ne4 Be5
15. Ng5 {but Black easily equalised in the following game} Nf6 16. dxc6 bxc6
17. Nf3 Bg4 18. h3 Bxf3 19. Qxf3 d5 {1/2-1/2 (51) Wan,Y (2477)-Ma,Q (2609)
China 2015}) 14... cxd5 $1 {Creates an isolated pawn, but the Black player
correclty evaluated that his piece activity will be sufficient to compensate
for this factor.} 15. Qxd5 Qc7 16. Qd3 Be6 17. Ne3 Rd8 18. c3 d5 19. Nc2 Nd6
20. Nd4 Qb6 21. Nxe6 fxe6 {and Black was fine in Harikrishna, P (2743)-So,W 
(2776) Batumi GEO 2018}) (11. Bf4 Rxe1 12. Qxe1 Ne8 13. c3 d5 {all this is
well-known theory} 14. Nd2 g6 (14... Nd6) ({and} 14... Bf5 {are two other
solid options for Black}) 15. Qe3 Ng7 16. Nf3 c6 17. a4 $146 ({Black achieved
a very comfortable draw after} 17. Re1 Be6 18. Ne5 Qa5 19. a3 Re8 20. Nd3 Qd8
21. Qd2 Bf5 22. Rxe8+ Qxe8 23. Qe3 Qxe3 {1/2-1/2 (23) Vachier Lagrave,M (2796)
-Grischuk,A (2742) Sharjah 2017}) 17... h5 $6 {There was no reason to allow
a4-a5.} ({Black should have played} 17... a5 $1) 18. a5 a6 19. b4 Nf5 20. Qd2
Nd6 21. Re1 {and suddenly Black's position became unpleasant. Hracek,Z (2557)
-Lopez Martinez,J (2581) Batumi GEO 2018}) 11... Rxe1 12. Qxe1 Ne8 {Black has
other moves as well, but the text recently dominates in GM games} 13. d5 {
Surprisingly this move has been played only once before the Olympiad.} ({
Usually White continued} 13. Bf4 d5 {with a very high percentage of draws.})
13... c6 $146 {this is more challenging than} (13... d6 14. Bd3 g6 15. Nd2 {
which looks slightly more pleasant for White Ozturk,H (1816)-Abdumalik,Z (2333)
Kocaeli 2014}) 14. Nd2 {Another game saw} (14. Be3 cxd5 15. Qd2 Nc7 16. Na3 {
White has sufficient compensation for the pawn, but hardly more} d6 17. Nc2 Bf5
18. Nb4 Be4 19. Rd1 a5 20. Nc2 Qd7 21. a3 Re8 {with an equal position.
Evantually White overpushed and lost. McShane,L (2672)-Radjabov,T (2751)
Batumi 2018}) 14... cxd5 15. Nf3 d6 16. Be3 Nc7 17. Qd2 Bd7 18. g3 Bc6 19. Bg2
Ne6 20. Rd1 {Once again White has compensation, but cannot pose Black any
problems.} Qa5 21. a3 h6 {and it was equal in Giri,A (2780)-Caruana,F (2827)
Batumi 2018} *

