1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 {There have been several interesting games in the Tarrasch
variation.} 3. Nd2 c5 {Nowadays Black's most popular option.} 4. exd5 {White's
most popular choice.} exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Be2 {A playable alternative to the
main move.} (6. Bb5 {This is mostly played. For those who are intersted in
more details, I can recommend Mihail Marin's wonderful database on this
subject.}) 6... Nf6 7. O-O c4 $5 {A very interesting attempt to challenge
White's set-up.} ({Much more popular are} 7... cxd4) ({and} 7... Be7) 8. b3 $1
{Definitely White's critical reaction to Black's provocative move.} c3 $5 {
Very aggressive and risky approach.} ({After the normal move} 8... cxb3 {
White retains the slightly better chances after} 9. axb3 Bd6 10. Bb2 O-O 11.
Ne5) 9. Nb1 Ne4 10. Qe1 Bb4 11. Bd3 ({Black's idea can be seen in the
following line:} 11. a3 Ba5 12. b4 Bc7 13. Nxc3 O-O 14. Be3 Re8 $44 {with
interesting compensation.}) 11... f5 $6 $146 {Black is trying to improve over
the previous game, which saw} (11... Qe7 $2 12. a3 Ba5 13. b4 Bb6 14. Nxc3 $16
{and White just won a pawn in Oltra Caurin,R (2425)-Garcia Cortes,J Mislata
1992}) ({I would suggest the following new idea} 11... O-O $5 $146 {, which
looks pretty playable after} 12. a3 Ba5 13. b4 {or} (13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Qxe4 Re8
15. Qd3 Bg4 $44) 13... Bb6 14. Nxc3 Re8 $44 {in both cases with interesting
compensation.}) 12. a3 Qa5 {I assume this is the point of Black previous play}
({, since} 12... Ba5 13. b4 Bb6 14. Bg5 Qd6 15. Nxc3 {is just clearly better
for White.}) 13. axb4 $1 {Very strong sacrifice} Qxa1 14. Ba3 a5 {logically
trying to free the queen.} 15. bxa5 Rxa5 {Muzychuk,M (2533)-Javakhishvili,L 
(2475) Batumi GEO 2018 White should have played} 16. Bd6 $1 $146 Kf7 17. Ne5+
Nxe5 18. dxe5 $36 {and Black's position is very dangerous.} *

