1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 {There have been several interesting games in the Tarrasch
variation.} 3. Nd2 c5 {Nowadays Black's most popular option.} 4. exd5 Qxd5 5.
Ngf3 cxd4 6. Bc4 Qd7 {This move was exclusively played in Batumi. Recently
more and more we could see Black deviate from the main move 6...Qd6, playing
either 6...Qd7 or 6...Qd8.} 7. O-O Nc6 8. Nb3 ({Another game in Batumi featured
} 8. Qe2 a6 9. a4 {It is hard to believe this line is dangerous for Black, but
the following game got really interesting} Nf6 10. Nb3 Bd6 (10... Qc7 {is a
relatively safe line for Black.}) 11. Rd1 e5 12. Nbxd4 Nxd4 13. Rxd4 {Very
aggressive approach. The positional alternative is} (13. Nxd4 Qe7 14. Nb3 e4 {
Black has scored pretty well with this move, but I believe White can easily
improve on his play.} ({In my view the following novelty is very reasonable} 
14... Bg4 $5 15. f3 Be6 {with balanced play.}) 15. Bg5 Qe5 {and now the new}
16. g3 $146 {is definitely more interesting than 16.f4 , which occured in both
games} Qxg5 17. Rxd6 O-O 18. Qe3 $14 {and White's chances seem preferable.})
13... Qe7 14. Rxd6 $5 {Very interesting exchange sacrifice.} ({In case of} 14.
Rh4 O-O 15. Bg5 {Black showed the path to equality in the following game} Bf5
16. Bd3 e4 17. Bxe4 Rae8 18. Re1 Bxe4 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 20. Rxe4 Rxe4 21. Qxe4 Qxb2
$11 {0-1 (44) Smith,B (2441)-Nyzhnyk,I (2612) Philadelphia 2017}) 14... Qxd6
15. b3 {Obviously the point} e4 ({The alternative looks reasonable as well:} 
15... Be6 16. Ba3 Bxc4 17. Qxc4 Qc6 18. Qxc6+ bxc6 19. Nxe5 c5 20. Bxc5 Nd7 21.
Nxd7 Kxd7 $13 {Black was able to hold this endgame in Nikitenko,M (2365)-Zhuk,
I (2144) Rogachev 2018}) 16. Ba3 Qf4 17. Qe1 $5 ({In case of the natural} 17.
Re1 {Black holds the position in the following way} Be6 18. Bxe6 fxe6 19. Qc4
Kf7 20. Bc1 Qd6 {Black's last three moves were pretty much the only ones} 21.
Ng5+ Kg6 22. h4 h5 $1 {Black is out of danger Melia,S (2393)-Kashlinskaya,A 
(2450) Wroclaw 2016}) 17... Be6 18. g3 $4 {White just blundered his knight and
the game was over.} (18. Qa5 Rc8 $2 ({Black's best defence here is} 18... Rd8
19. Re1 Nd5 {with a complex game.}) 19. Ne5 $36 {White's initiative was too
powerful for Black. Lagunow,R (2403)-Jarmula,L (2504) Manavgat 2018}) 18...
Qxf3 19. Be2 Qf5 $19 {0-1 (37) Mikkelsen,N (2467)-Studer,N (2484) Batumi GEO
2018 [Home]}) 8... a6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Bc5 {This rarely seen move
appears to be quite playable.} ({The two Black main continuations are} 10...
Qc7 {and}) (10... Nf6) 11. Be3 Nf6 12. Qf3 $2 $146 ({An unfortunate piece
sacrifice. A normal continuation here would be} 12. Re1 {although I didn't
notice any problems for Black after} O-O 13. Bb3 b6 14. Nf3 Qc7 {, which was
played it several games.}) 12... Bxd4 13. Rad1 e5 14. Bxd4 (14. c3 {doesn't
work either:} Qc7 15. cxd4 Qxc4 16. dxe5 Ng4 {Black should convert his
material advantage.}) 14... exd4 15. Rfe1+ Kd8 $1 {only not} (15... Kf8 $2 16.
Qa3+ Kg8 17. Re7 $18) 16. Qg3 Re8 17. Qxg7 Rxe1+ 18. Rxe1 Qd6 19. Bxf7 {
Gonzalez Vidal,Y (2566)-Pelletier,Y (2544) Batumi GEO 2018 and now the most
precise move would have been} Kc7 $146 20. Be6+ Bd7 $17 {would be clearly
better for Black.} *

